ROOT CAUSE: `program.cpp:10` uses `for (size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--)`, but `size_t` is unsigned, so `i >= 0` is always true. In GDB, the first call to `print_reverse` had `v.size() == 3`, so `i` started at `2`, then became `1`, then `0`; after printing `v[0]`, `i--` wrapped around to `18446744073709551615`, and `i >= 0` still evaluated to `true`. The next iteration therefore evaluates `v[i]` with a huge unsigned index, producing an out-of-bounds read under AddressSanitizer; for an empty vector the initialization `v.size() - 1` would also immediately underflow to that same maximum value.

LOCAL FIX: Replace the unsigned reverse loop with an idiom that never tests an unsigned value against zero after decrementing. A minimal safe edit is:
```diff
 static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {
-    for (size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
+    for (size_t i = v.size(); i-- > 0;) {
         std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);
     }
 }
```
This starts one past the last valid index, decrements before use, prints indices `size-1` down to `0`, and for an empty vector the condition `i-- > 0` is false before any access occurs.

GLOBAL FIX: Avoid hand-written index arithmetic for reverse traversal when the container already provides bounded iteration. For example, implement this pattern using reverse iterators:
```cpp
for (auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it) {
    std::printf("%d\n", *it);
}
```
More broadly, prefer iterator/range-based APIs or a small helper such as `print_reverse(std::span<const int>)` using reverse iterators, and enable warnings such as `-Wall -Wextra -Wtype-limits`/`-Wsign-compare` so impossible unsigned comparisons like `i >= 0` are caught during compilation.

